comments.text:
I feel like I should explain what was in this video, because many people who are not into computers will not understand what the difference is and what was compared here.
The thing is that the 5060ti video card itself is capable of running at 1440p in absolutely any game, its power allows it. What we can see in games that consume significantly less than 8GB of video memory (not RAM, don't confuse it) in such games the frame rate (fps) is absolutely the same and the frame time is equally smooth and your video card is fully loaded and works normally.
But as soon as the game starts to consume more than 8GB of video memory, the frame rate starts to decrease and the frame time becomes ragged, this happens because the video card starts to run out of its own video memory and it starts to access the RAM, which is much slower and has large delays, from which we get lower fps and sometimes we can get "microfreezes".
Do you know why this video doesn't have a game like "Indiana Jones and the Great Circle"? Because the 8GB version of the 5060ti video card refuses to run at 1440p, it can only run at minimum settings and will be limited by 8GB of memory every time, while the video card will give out 150-200 fps, which tells us that its power is enough for this game, but there is no memory. In turn, the 16GB version of the 5060ti easily runs at maximum settings at 1440p and you can easily play Indiana Jones and the Great Circle. Now think about whether you should buy the 5060ti 8GB, because in the future, there will only be more and more games like "Indiana Jones and the Great Circle"
